The Mechanism: 
One single agent is initially flagged as "informed" (visualized in yellow) . 
As the agents move autonomously under standard flocking rules, the informed agent continuously checks its immediate radius. 
If a susceptible (uninformed) agent spends time within this localized radius, there is a set probability per frame that the signal will be successfully transferred to them.  

Emergent Cascade: 
The visualization effectively demonstrates the dynamics of network effects. 
Initially, the spread is slow, remaining confined to the "Patient Zero" agents immediate sub-flock. 
However, because the overarching flock occasionally splits, merges, and intersects, newly informed agents carry the signal to distant clusters.  

Exponential Growth: Similar to the spread of a virus or a viral social media post, the rate of transmission accelerates exponentially. 
Once a critical mass of agents becomes informed, the number of transmission vectors multiplies, causing the entire population to receive the danger or food signal in a very brief window of time, all stemming from local interactions without a central broadcasting system.
